A glimpse into flight data for Pittsburgh, PA in 1988 and 2007: With a focus on delays and the month of November

October 31, 2020

What are the main features of interest in the datasets?¶

There are many interesting aspects of the flight data in both 88 and 07, but 7 main features of interest stand out in this dataset at this point:

  • The most popular month for travel in 88 and 07 (November will be looked at due to it being my birth month and the overall theme of this visual data exploration
  • The most popular day of the week for travel in 88 and 07
  • The most popular origins for flights arriving in Pittsburgh
  • The most popular destinations for flights departing from Pittsburgh
  • The length of flights
  • The length of delays for flights that experience them (Delays will only be examined in 2007 as the 1988 data does not have the same information)
  • The most common type of delay

What features in the dataset will help support the investigation into the features of interest?¶

The first five main features of interest (listed above) are easily examined utilizing the following columns:

  1. Month
  2. DayOfWeek
  3. Origin
  4. Destination
  5. ActualElapsedTime

However, the last two items are a little more difficult to handle. It may not be the most tidy method of organizing this data, but a secondary delays dataframe will be created with a categorical column which details the type of delay each flight experienced. The CarrierDelay, WeatherDelay, NASDelay, SecurityDelay, and LateAircraftDelay columns feature delay time in minutes. These columns will be used for their literal delay data and compiled to create both a total delay column and a delay type column, as needed.

Continuing the Theme¶

Given the aforementioned timing related to the conclusion of this class and my 32nd birthday, an examination of the most popular date, day of the week, origin, and destination for flights in November of 1988 (and 2007) may also be examined as a part of the bivariate and multivariate exploration.

Regardless, the next step will be to create a copy of the original dataframes, further examine the data, and begin any cleaning and reorganization of the data which is necessary.

Data Exploration ¶

As discussed earlier, there are at least seven aspects of this data which will be examined in greater detail. They are:

  • The most popular month for travel in 88 and 07
  • The most popular day of the week for travel in 88 and 07
  • The most popular origins for flights arriving in Pittsburgh
  • The most popular destinations for flights departing from Pittsburgh
  • The length of flights
  • The length of delays for flights that experience them
  • The most common type of delay

They will undergo Univariate Exploration and some many be combined in bivariate or multivariate exploration if their results encourage a deeper exploration.

Univariate Exploration ¶

1. Most Popular Month to Fly¶

Please take note that these figures utilize y-variable limits to more close exaine the difference between each month's flight data. The differences between one month to the other is not based from 0, but from 18,000 in 1988 and 7000 in 2007. The greatest difference between months is less than 3000 flights in 1988 and just over 2000 flights in 2007.

It can be seen that travel to and from Pittsburgh is higher in the summer months, especially in 1988. February is very low for travel in both years and the winter months see less travel overall. It should also be noted that there is a significant difference in the amount of flights in 1988 and 2007. There are many factors which contributed to this difference, but it does not appear to have changed the preferred time to travel in too significant a way, mosly a reversal of preference over flying in December in 2018 and in January in 2007.

2. Most Popular Day of the Week to Fly¶

Please take note that these figures utilize y-variable limits to more close exaine the difference between each day of the week's flight data. The differences between one day of the week to the other is not based from 0, but from 33,000 in 1988 and 11500 in 2007. The greatest difference between days of the week is less than 2000 flights in 1988 and just over 3000 flights in 2007.

Like the charts related to montly travel, there is a similar pattern of weekday travel being higher in both 1988 and 2007. Weekends do not see as many flights, though Sundays received a significant uptick from 1988 to 2007. The higher values for weekday travel could suggest that travel related to business is more common in Pittsburgh, especially in 1988. Regardless, Saturday is the least preferred day to travel in both 1988 and 2007.

3. Most Popular Flight Origin¶

Similar to the previous figure, the majority of aiports which sent flights to Pittsburgh in 2007 sent less than 3000. However, there were 3 airports which still sent over 3000. They were Philadelphia at 3457 flights (overtaking Newark from 1988), Chicago O'Hare with 4386 flights and Atlanta with 4492 flights(overtaking O'Hare).

Now, for anyone who does not fly or know very much about air travel, there are smaller local airports, medium-sized regional airports, and large airports known as hubs. Atantla has become the busiest airport on the East Coast, so that is why it sends and receives so many flights to/from Pittsburgh, a "medium-sized" airport. Chicago, Detriot, Philadelphia, and the NYC airports are also larger airports than Pittsburgh, with some of them being hubs as well.

Due to this relationship of airports, the following figures related to destinations from Pittsburgh will also likely send the most flights to these significant hubs (to transfer to another flight) more than the regional(medium) or local(small) airports.

4. Most Popular Flight Destination¶

Flights originating in Pittsburgh usually went to each airport less than 3000 times in 1988. However, again, 6 airports received more than 3000 flights a year from Pittsburgh. These are the numbers for those 6 airports: LaGuardia in NYC received 3474 flights, Detroit received 3780 flights, Philadelphia received 3818 flights, Newark received 4434 flights, Atlanta received 5104 flights, and Chicago O'Hare received 6355 flights.

Similar to the previous graph, the majority of airports which received flights from Pittsburgh in 2007 received less than 2750 flights. In fact, 1/3 of the 45 airports received less than 250 flights from Pittsburgh. However, there were 3 airports which still received well more than 2750. They were Chicago O'Hare with 4284 flights, Philadelphia at 4305 flights (overtaking Newark and Chicago), and Atlanta with 4485 flights(overtaking O'Hare). Interestingly, Pittsburgh sent flights to 9 more airports than it received flights from in 2007. This is another example of how air travel through Pittsburgh changed over the 20 year period from 1988 to 2007.

5. Flight Length¶

In the 6 figures above you saw the basic histogram of flight time for both 1988 and 2007 and then saw it again directly next to its log equivalent. The log of the flight time data is much easier to interpret with a nice normal distribution, especially for flights in 1988. Most flights were between approximately 50 minutes and 100 minutes. Some short hoppers were less than 50 minutes and some long-hauls lasted upwards of 300 minutes (5 hours)! The data from 2007 suggests that flights to and from Pittsburgh were generally a little longer than in 1988. There were no flights with a time shorter than 40 minutes and a few more data points on the upper end of the distribution.

6. Delay Length¶

As these 5 histograms show, the data is heavily skewed to the right, with most delay times for each type of delay being less than 25 minutes long. However, please keep in mind that earlier wrangling of this data did drop some extreme data outliers (any delays longer than 200 minutes), but that was less than 600 flights of the over 26,000 in the original delays_07 df. This data could be examined with a log transformation for a little more clarity, but the overall message is that most delays are well under an hour if not less than 30 minutes.

However, what if you are unfortunate to be on a flight which is the victim of multiple delays? To examine this train of thought we will first create and look at the total delay time for each type of delay. Then we will use this information and make the first of several bivariate figures to further explore this data and other aspects of the univariate analysis.

The delay time by delay type figure shows that a late aircraft has acrued the most delay time in 2007 with 525,707 minutes or 365 days, 1 hour and 47 minutes! Perhaps surprisingly, weather did not result in nearly as much delay time in Pittsburgh in 2007, but still accumulated 68,972 minutes or 47 days 21 hours and 32 minutes worth of delays. Lastly, it is nice to note that less than 2,000 minutes of delays were attributed to security related issues in 2007.

Bivariate Exploration ¶

1. Total delay time and delay type¶

A lot of cleaning of the delays_07 sub dataframe went into creating the 19 different delay combinations you see in the above figure. There were actually more possible, but the data for pittsburgh delays did not feature some of the combinations. For example, no flight in or out of Pittsburgh in 2007 dealt with all 5 types of delays (thankfully)! However, a few did experience flights which dealt with every delay, but security! This figure shows the total delay time for each of their individual delay type combinations.

Late aircraft delays seems to lead to the largest outliers of the above data. While occuring individually, a late aircraft delay is very similar to Carrier, Weather, and NAS delays. Though, when it is combined with 1-2 other delay types it results in some larger outliers of close to or more than 350 minutes of combined delay time! Additionally, security delays are infrequent in all combinations, appearing in only 5 of the 19 delay combinations experienced. They also do not appear to do much to alter the overall delay time of any of their combinations. This was supported earlier by that delay type featuring a very small total delay time compared to the other delay categories when examined in the univariate analysis.

2. Busiest day of the week to travel by month¶

Before looking at anything else, it is important to note that both of the figures above feature an adjusted ylimit to look at the data more closely. In the 1988 plot the data starts at 2250 and in the 2007 figure it starts at 800. This means that the differences in flights are not quite as extreme as they appear when compared to one another.

Now, the above countplots appear to be filled with a lot of data, but it is really quite straightforward when you examine it piece by piece. Simply, each figure shows breaks the flight count down by month and then divides it up by the day of the week. For example, Saturdays in January of 2007 saw only around 900 total flights while Mondays, Tuesdays, and Wednesdays of the same month/year each had a total of around 1400 flights! If you recall, Saturdays were the least popular day of the week to travel overall in 1988 and 2007, so it is not surprising that it is the least preferred day of the week to travel in almost every month of both 1988 and 2007. 10/12 months in 2007 had it as the least popular, with March and June seeing Sunday as the least popular. In 1988 every month had Saturday as the least popular day to travel, excluding December which people traveled the least on Sundays.

What these figures allow you to efficiently see, which the two independent examinations in the univariate analysis did not, is that each month/day of the week has underlying patterns regarding flight count. Now, it is difficult to explain all of these trends, but if one wished to garner an even deeper understanding of why, for example, Thursdays and Fridays in November in 2007 had higher travel counts they could look at when major holidays fell in that particular month. As many people know, Thanksgiving in the US is always on a Thursday and is a big travel holiday. In 1988 Tuesday and Wednesday had the highest rate of travel in November, so maybe travel tendencies in Pittsburgh have changed or perhaps either 1988 or 2007 was an abnormality for November. It is hard to draw real conclusions without more yearly data, but general observations like these can be drawn for many of the Months/Day of the Week combinations.

3. Flight Delays by Day of the Week in Pittsburgh in November of 2007¶

It can very quickly been seen that Monday had the largest amount of total delay time in November of 2007. Also, most days of the week dealt with delay times ranging from around 25 minutes to 65 minutes.

However, there are a few more aspects of these bivariate figures which could be further explored. For instance, what type of delay combinations were most responsible for delays each day of the week experienced in 2007? Hopefully this question, and maybe more, will be answered in the following Multivariate Exploration.

Multivariate Exploration ¶

1. Average Total Delay Time for the Top 5 Delay Types divided by Day of the Week¶

Thanks to the colorbar it is very easy to immediately identify that NAS delays (of these top 5 delay types) had the smallest average delay for every day of the week. However, the combination of a Late Aircraft and an NAS delay resulted in the highest average total delay time for every day of the week. Earlier the bivariate analysis already indicated that the combination of Late Aircraft with other delay types resulted in higher total delay time and that pattern holds true, even when the data is additionally grouped by day of the week.

The same color palette is used for this first chart as the same delay type combinations were utilized when examining the November only dataframe. As you can see, there is less consistency in the data than the overall 2007 delays dataframe. Late Aircraft and NAS/Late Aircraft delays are both top, but they rotate the number one spot depending upon the day of the week, when previously the NAS/Late Aircraft delay type took the top for every day. Additionally, NAS is still consistently low, but it no longer can claim the lowest average delay time for these delay type combinations.

Similar to the above heat maps, but still very much its own. A different color pallet was used to further differentiate between the two top 5 delay type choices (2007 vs Nov-07). It can be easily seen, with the bright yellow, that the November dataframe shows an increased emphasis on the 'Carrier, Late Aircraft' delay type, which was not featured in the overall 2007 delays top 5 delay types. In fact, this combination features the 2nd and 3rd highest average total delay times for all three heatmaps, despite this category not making it to the top 5 of the overall 2007 delay dataframe. However, it needs to be noted that the second most prominent delay type is again the stand-alone Late Aircraft type which was also very consistently 1st or 2nd in the previous figures as well.

2. Destinations on November 20th 2007, Delay Types, and the Total Elapsed Time¶

As mentioned above, this final figure only features 37 data points. So, that makes the analysis of this particular figure extremely limited, but it did capture the desired information efficiently. Performing this same type of analysis on a larger portion or the whole dataframe would have required the limiting of destinations and delay types, as this type of figure would have been overwhelmed with data points quickly.

What this figure can tell us is that NAS delays were the most frequent(noted by the number of blue data points), followed by the NAS/Late Aircraft combination(orange data points). Additionally, Philadelphia was the top Destination. It also shows that the lone flight to Denver was the longest flight of the 37 which departed Pittsburgh on November 20th. This is likely due to both its distance (relative to other airpots) and the NAS/Late Aircraft delay it experienced.
